{"title_page": "I Am (Yo Gotti album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Am\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Yo Gotti]]\n| cover      = Yo Gotti I Am.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2013|11|19|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = 2012&ndash;13\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 49:28\n| label      = [[Collective Music Group|Collective]], [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*Benny Pough  {{small|([[executive producer|exec]].)}}\n*[[Sha Money XL]] {{small|(exec.)}}\n*[[Yo Gotti]] {{small|(exec.)}}\n*[[Arthur McArthur]]\n*[[Cool & Dre]]\n*David Versis\n*[[Honorable C.N.O.T.E.]]\n*Canei Finch\n*Greedy Money\n*[[DJ Infamous|Infamous]]\n*Jesse Wilson\n*[[Metro Boomin]]\n*Phatboiz\n*[[The HBK Gang|P-Lo]]\n*[[Lee On The Beats]]\n*[[Rich Homie Quan]]\n*Trauma Tone\n*The Youngstars\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Live from the Kitchen]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[The Art of Hustle]]\n| next_year  = 2016\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = I Am\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Act Right (Yo Gotti song)|Act Right]]\n | single1date = {{start date|2013|7|23|mf=yes}}\n | single2     = King Shit\n | single2date = {{start date|2013|10|7|mf=yes}}\n | single3     = Cold Blood\n | single3date = {{start date|2013|10|31|mf=yes}}\n | single4     = [[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\n | single4date = {{start date|2013|11|15|mf=yes}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''I Am''''' is the seventh [[studio album]] by American [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] recording artist [[Yo Gotti]]. The album was released on November 19, 2013, by [[Epic Records|Epic]] and CMG.<ref name=\"apple1\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/i-am/id722411780|title=iTunes - Music - I Am by Yo Gotti |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-11-19 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> The album features [[guest appearance]]s from [[T.I.]], [[Ne-Yo]], [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]], [[Rich Homie Quan]], [[J. Cole]], [[Young Jeezy|Jeezy]], [[Meek Mill]], and [[YG (rapper)|YG]], among others. The album was supported by the singles \"[[Act Right (Yo Gotti song)|Act Right]]\" featuring YG and Jeezy, \"King Shit\" featuring T.I., \"Cold Blood\" featuring J. Cole and Canei Finch and \"[[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\" featuring Rich Homie Quan. The first and fourth singles were later certified gold by the [[RIAA]].\n\n==Background==\nOn May 28, 2013, [[Yo Gotti]] announced that his sixth studio album would be titled ''I Am''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Homie |first=Big |url=http://rapradar.com/2013/07/31/new-video-yo-gotti-fuck-you/ |title=New Video: Yo Gotti \"Fuck You\" |publisher=Rap Radar |date=2013-07-31 |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref> In July 2013, it was announced that the album would be released on November 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Homie |first=Big |url=http://rapradar.com/2013/07/31/new-video-yo-gotti-fuck-you/ |title=New Video: Yo Gotti \"Fuck You\" |publisher=Rap Radar |date=2013-07-31 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> On August 22, 2013, he announced the ''I Am'' Tour Dates, a tour in promotion of ''I Am'' which ran from September 14, 2013, until November 19, 2013, with supporting acts including [[YG (rapper)|YG]], Zed Zilla, Shy Glizzy and [[Cash Out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/08/yo-gotti-announces-i-am-release-date-and-tour-dates-with-yg/ |title=Yo Gotti Announces 'I Am' Release Date And Tour Dates With YG - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=2013-08-22 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> On September 2, 2013, Yo Gotti released the mixtape ''Nov 19th: The Mixtape'' in promotion for the album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mayorga |first=Dean |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25324/title.yo-gotti-nov-19th-the-mixtape-cover-art-tracklisting-download-mixtape-stream |title=Yo Gotti \"Nov 19th: The Mixtape\" Cover Art, Tracklisting, Download & Mixtape Stream |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2013-09-04 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn a December 2013, interview with Mikey T The Movie Star, Yo Gotti spoke about how the album was received, saying: \"We gettin' nothin' but good, positive feedback from the album. The numbers going fairly well. Most important to me, the fans loved it. Fans fuck wit' it. ...Just givin' the people what they want. I've seen a lot of growth with this album. We doing different platforms, TV shows, we doing shows in different markets. Just being on different blog sites. I'm seeing a lot of different things coming. I guess it's because of the growth of the material that I put out on this album.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper |first=Roman |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26689/title.yo-gotti-says-he-s-grown-with-i-am-release |title=Yo Gotti Says He's Grown With \"I Am\" Release |publisher=HipHop DX |date= |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\nOn July 23, 2013, the album's first single \"[[Act Right (Yo Gotti song)|Act Right]]\" featuring [[Young Jeezy|Jeezy]] and [[YG (rapper)|YG]] was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/act-right-feat.-jeezy-yg-single/id672806616 |title=iTunes - Music - Act Right (feat. Jeezy & YG) - Single by Yo Gotti |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-07-23 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> On July 24, 2013, the music video for \"Act Right\" featuring Jeezy and YG was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2013/07/24/video-yo-gotti-f-young-jeezy-yg-act-right/ |title=Video: Yo Gotti f/ Young Jeezy & YG \u2013 'Act Right' |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2013-07-24 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> \"Act Right\" has since peaked at number 100 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/431628/yo-gotti/chart |title=Yo Gotti - Chart history |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=2013-10-22}}</ref> On October 7, 2013, the album's second official single \"King Shit\" featuring [[T.I.]] was released to [[mainstream urban]] radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1090&SingleID=3747 |title=Frequency News |publisher=Frequency News |date=2013-09-11 |access-date=2013-10-03 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005010142/http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1090&SingleID=3747 |archive-date=2013-10-05 |df= }}</ref> On October 15, 2013, the music video for \"King Shit\" featuring T.I. was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2013/10/15/video-yo-gotti-f-ti-king-shit/ |title=Video: Yo Gotti f/ T.I. \u2013 'King Sh*t' |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2013-10-15 |accessdate=2013-10-22}}</ref> \"King Shit\" has since peaked at five on the US ''Billboard'' [[Bubbling Under R&B/Hip-Hop Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/277486/ti/chart?f=345 |title=T.I. - Chart history |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n\nOn October 27, 2013, Yo Gotti premiered the album's third single, \"Cold Blood\" featuring rapper [[J. Cole]] and Canei Finch.<ref>{{cite web|author=Yo Gotti <!--end div name--> Follow @YoGottiKOM &nbsp; |url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/yo-gotti-cold-blood |title=Yo Gotti ft. J. Cole - Cold Blood &#124; Listen |publisher=Djbooth.net |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref> Four days later on October 31, \"Cold Blood\" was serviced to mainstream urban radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1113&SingleID=3781 |title=Frequency News |publisher=Frequency News |date=2013-10-31 |accessdate=2013-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109123649/http://www.frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1113&SingleID=3781 |archive-date=2013-11-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Then on November 19, 2013, \"Cold Blood\" was serviced to [[rhythmic contemporary]] radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fmqb.com/article.asp?id=16691 |title=Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Arbitron Ratings, Music News and more! |magazine=FMQB |access-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403141710/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691 |archive-date=2014-04-03 }}</ref> On February 5, 2014, the music video was released for \"Cold Blood\" featuring J. Cole and Canei Finch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/02/05/video-yo-gotti-f-j-cole-cold-blood/ |title=Video: Yo Gotti f/ J. Cole \u2013 'Cold Blood' |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2014-02-05 |accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2013, the music video was released for \"LeBron James\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/11/yo-gotti-lebron-james-video |title=Yo Gotti \"LeBron James\" Video |magazine=Complex |date=2013-11-20 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref> On December 10, 2013, the music video was released for \"Don't Come Around\" featuring Kendall Morgan.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/12/yo-gotti-f-kendall-morgan-dont-come-around |title=Yo Gotti f/ Kendall Morgan \"Don't Come Around\" |magazine=Complex |accessdate=2013-12-11}}</ref> On November 15, 2013, \"[[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\" featuring [[Rich Homie Quan]] was released as the album's fourth single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/I-Know-Explicit/dp/B00GJ4LRJ4 |title=I Know feat. Rich Homie Quan [Explicit&#93;: Yo Gotti feat. Rich Homie Quan: MP3 Downloads |date=2013-11-15 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref> In January 2014, it was serviced to urban contemporary radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promoonly.com/listings/view.php?issueid=15533&backup-view=1 |title=View Listing &#124; Promo Only: Music & Music Video |publisher=Promo Only |date= |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref> On May 1, 2014, the music video was released for \"I Know\" featuring Rich Homie Quan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/videos/id.16217/title.yo-gotti-f-rich-homie-quan-i-know- |title=Yo Gotti f. Rich Homie Quan - \"I Know\" |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2014-05-01 |accessdate=2014-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC=64/100<ref name=\"metacritic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/i-am/yo-gotti |title=I Am Reviews |website=Metacritic |date=2014-01-08 |accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|author=David Jeffries |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-am-mw0002585418 |title=I Am - Yo Gotti &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |accessdate=2013-11-19}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Daily Cougar]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thedailycougar.com/2013/11/23/review-yo-gottis-album/ |title=Review: Yo Gotti's album, 'I Am' |newspaper=The Daily Cougar |date=2013-11-23 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[HipHopDX]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"hiphopdx1\">{{cite web |last=Grant |first=Ronald |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.2184/title.yo-gotti-i-am |title=Yo Gotti - I Am |publisher=HipHop DX |date= |accessdate=2013-11-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131121013047/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.2184/title.yo-gotti-i-am |archive-date=2013-11-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Memphis Flyer]]''\n| rev4Score = (positive)<ref name=\"memphisflyer1\">{{cite web|last=Goggans |first=Louis |url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/CallingtheBluff/archives/2013/11/24/reppin-for-memphis-my-review-of-yo-gottis-i-am |title=Reppin' For Memphis: My Review of Yo Gotti's I Am |publisher=Memphis Flyer |date=2013-11-24 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>\n| rev5 = RapReviews\n| rev5Score = 4.5/10<ref name=\"rapreviews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2013_12_yogotti-iam.html |title=Yo Gotti :: I Am :: CMG/Epic Records |publisher=Rapreviews.com |date=2013-12-17 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''\n| rev6Score = (positive)<ref name=\"vibe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/review-yo-gottis-i-am-excels-using-familiar-script |title=Review: Yo Gotti's 'I Am' Excels Using A Familiar Script |publisher=Vibe |date=2013-11-21 |accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|2|4}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Jerry Shriver, Elysa Gardner, Brian Mansfield, USA TODAY |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/11/18/jake-bugg-yo-gotti-5-finger-death-punch-listen-up/3630325/ |title=Listen Up: Jake Bugg, Yo Gotti, 5 Finger Death Punch |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2013-11-19 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''\n| rev8Score = 3/5 (L)<ref name=\"xxlmag1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/reviews/2013/11/yo-gotti-i-am-album-review/ |title=Yo Gotti Mostly Stays True To His Soulful Memphis Sound On 'I Am' |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=2013-11-21 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''I Am'' was met with generally positive reviews from [[music criticism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 64, based on 5 reviews.<ref name=\"metacritic1\"/> David Jeffries of [[AllMusic]] gave the album four out of five stars, saying \"Like so many rappers who play it street level and live and die by the mixtape game, Memphis man Yo Gotti has maintained an uneasy relationship with the official album. His early work was indie to a fault, with long-players sounding patched together from mixtape numbers and other related whatnot, while his mainstream debut, 2012's ''Live from the Kitchen'', suffered from its long birthing process, sounding patched together on the million-dollar level with too much input from the marketing department. Good news for fans who stuck it out this long is that ''I Am'' is the moment when the skies clear, as the album comes on strong with a hard-hitting set of openers, and then, the high quality is maintained with a set of easy-flowing supportive songs that broaden the LP spectrum, all without leaving Gotti's comfort zone.\"<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> Ronald Grant of [[HipHopDX]] gave the album two and a half stars out of five, saying \"At the end of the day, ''I Am''\u2019s overall passable production and flashes of potency and strength keep it afloat for a time. And Gotti deserves commendation for his talent at bringing an explicit rawness, reality and affection to his autobiographical bars. But even those considerations aren\u2019t enough to make this album worth more than a few listens, sadly relying on a continuous set of monotonous hooks and overly used trap beats that saturate a strong majority of current popular Rap music.\"<ref name=\"hiphopdx1\"/> Reed Jackson of ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' gave the album an L, saying \"On the majority of ''I Am'', he stays rooted in the ideas and melodies that he\u2019s been refining since he first dropped ''From Da Dope Game 2 Da Rap Game'' over 10 year ago. The self-proclaimed \u201cKing Of Memphis\u201d has lived up to his title again, and perhaps this album will help him continue his reign for another 10 years.\"<ref name=\"xxlmag1\"/>\n\nPaul Cantor of ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' gave the album a positive review, saying \"If there\u2019s one glaring downside to ''I Am'', it\u2019s that a handful of songs sound, well, a lot like other songs. From the flows to the production, \u201cAct Right\u201d mimicks Young Jeezy's \u201cR.I.P.,\u201d and \u201cLebron James\u201d apes Juicy J's \u201cBandz A Make Her Dance.\u201d There are others. One on the one hand you applaud Gotti for implementing a hit-making formula so effectively, and after all, songs sounding like other songs is not an uncommon thing. But on the other hand, why couldn't Gotti couldn't come up with his own blueprint for smash records? Maybe after all these years he didn't want to leave too much up to chance. Not sure we can be mad at that.\"<ref name=\"vibe\"/> Grant Jones of RapReviews gave the album a 4.5 out of 10, saying \"This album slams harder than a body slam from Sticky Fingaz, and much like Onyx, ruthless misogyny runs throughout \"''I Am''\", with \u2018bitch' and \u2018nigga' in every other bar. At times you'd wish Gotti had done what DMX used to do and recorded two versions (of each song!), or even better, put some thought in to his writing. If you can get past the ignorance, this is enjoyable for what it is - an album to be played loudly in your car, with the windows down and a middle finger up to anybody who looks at you disapprovingly.\"<ref name=\"rapreviews1\"/> Louis Goggans of the ''[[Memphis Flyer]]'' gave the album a positive review, saying \"Gotti\u2019s transition from dominating the underground rap circuit to enjoying mainstream success with hits like \u201c5 Star\u201d and \u201cMen Lie, Women Lie\u201d convey that hard work pays off. And he continues to utilize the very same work ethic that's brought him to this point in his career on his latest project. Although Gotti doesn't sway too far from his usual topics on the album, he doesn't display any signs of decline creatively either. After more than 10 years in the game, Gotti still has the ability to provide listeners with quality music and this is evident with ''I Am''.\"<ref name=\"memphisflyer1\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted at number seven on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 48,000 copies in the United States, becoming Gotti's highest charting and best-selling album to date at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26422/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-11-24-2013|last=Tardio|first=Andres|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 11/24/2013|magazine=HipHopDX|date=2013-11-27|accessdate=2013-11-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131130024046/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26422/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-11-24-2013|archive-date=2013-11-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> In its second week the album sold 19,000 more copies.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26489/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-1-2013|last=Tardio|first=Andres|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 12/1/2013|magazine=HipHopDX|date=2013-12-04|accessdate=2013-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213000209/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26489/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-1-2013|archive-date=2013-12-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> In its third week the album sold 11,000 more copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26580/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-8-2013 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Week Ending 12/8/2013 |publisher=HipHop DX |date= |accessdate=2013-12-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213060438/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26580/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-8-2013/ |archive-date=2013-12-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In its fourth week the album sold 10,000 more copies.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26666/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-15-2013|last=Tardio|first=Andres|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 12/15/2013|magazine=HipHopDX|date=2013-12-18|accessdate=2013-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219031704/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26666/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-15-2013|archive-date=2013-12-19|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of August 2015, the album has sold 212,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150825183753/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= August 25, 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |website=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Ceremony\n! Category\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2014\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[2014 BET Hip Hop Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nostro|first1=Lauren|title=Here Are the 2014 BET Hip-Hop Award Nominees|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/09/2014-bet-hip-hop-award-nominees|work=Complex|publisher=Complex Media|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|Album of the Year\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1 = I Am\n| note1 = \n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Yo Gotti|Mario Mims]]|Philipp Hurtt|Walter Sigler|Kazumi Tabarak}} \n| extra1 = [[Cool & Dre]]\n| length1 = 3:04\n\n| title2 = Don't Come Around\n| note2 = featuring Kendall Morgan\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Mims|Kendall Morgan|Alexander Izquierdo}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|[[DJ Infamous|Infamous]]|Alexander Izquierdo}}\n| length2 = 3:10\n\n| title3 = [[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\n| note3 = featuring [[Rich Homie Quan]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Mim|Denzel Foster|Jay King|[[Rich Homie Quan|Dequantes Lamar]]|Thomas McElroy}} \n| extra3 = {{hlist|Trauma Tone|[[Rich Homie Quan]]}}\n| length3 = 4:19\n\n| title4 = Sorry\n| note4 = \n| writer4 = Mims\n| extra4 = Greedy Money\n| length4 = 3:16\n\n| title5 = F-U\n| note5 = featuring [[Meek Mill]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Mims|[[Meek Mill|Robert Williams]]|Millie Jackson|Randy Klein}}\n| extra5 = Infamous\n| length5 = 3:05\n\n| title6 = Pride To the Side\n| note6 = \n| writer6 = {{hlist|Mims|Robert Daniels|Matt Brox|Everett Orr}}\n| extra6 = The Youngstars\n| length6 = 4:21\n\n| title7 = Cold Blood\n| note7 = featuring [[J. Cole]] & Canei Finch\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Mims|[[J. Cole|Jermaine Cole]]|[[Dale Warren]]|Canei Finch}} \n| extra7 = Canei Finch\n| length7 = 5:11\n\n| title8 = LeBron James\n| note8 = \n| writer8 = {{hlist|Mims|[[Lee On The Beats|Anthony Norris]]}}\n| extra8 = [[Lee On The Beats]]\n| length8 = 3:13\n\n| title9 = Die a Real Nigga\n| note9 = \n| writer9 = {{hlist|Mims|[[Honorable C.N.O.T.E.|Carlton Mays Jr.]]}} \n| extra9 = [[Honorable C.N.O.T.E.]]\n| length9 = 4:29\n\n| title10 = King Shit \n| note10 = featuring [[T.I.]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Mims|[[T.I.|Clifford Harris]]|Asha Bhosle|Mahenra Kakpoor}}\n| extra10 = {{hlist|David Versis|[[Arthur McArthur]]}}\n| length10 = 3:31\n\n| title11 = Respect That You Earn\n| note11 = featuring [[Ne-Yo]] & [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]]\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Mims|[[Wale (rapper)|Olubowale Akintimehin]]|[[Ne-Yo|Shaffer Smith]]}}\n| extra11 = {{hlist|Jesse \"Corparal\" Wilson|Phatboiz|Kenton Dunson}} \n| length11 = 4:22\n\n| title12 = ION Want It\n| note12 =\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Mims|[[Metro Boomin|Leland Wayne]]}}\n| extra12 = [[Metro Boomin]]\n| length12 = 3:17\n\n| title13 = [[Act Right (Yo Gotti song)|Act Right]]\n| note13 = featuring [[Young Jeezy|Jeezy]] & [[YG (rapper)|YG]]\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Mims|[[YG (rapper)|Keenon Jackson]]|[[Young Jeezy|Jay Jenkins]]|[[The HBK Gang|Paulo Ytienza Rodriguez]]|Osten Harvey Jr.|Roger Troutman|[[The Notorious B.I.G.|Christopher Wallace]]|[[Iamsu!|Sudan Williams]]}} \n| extra13 = P-Lo\n| length13 = 4:10\t\n}}\n\n==Chart positions==\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (2013\u201314)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{Albumchart|Billboard200|7|artist=Yo Gotti|accessdate=November 28, 2013}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRandBHipHop|2|artist=Yo Gotti|accessdate=November 28, 2013}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2014)\n!Position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' 200<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2014/top-billboard-200-albums|title=2014 Year-End Charts \u2013 Billboard 200 Albums |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |accessdate=February 28, 2015}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|116\n|-\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Yo Gotti|title=I Am|award=Gold|type=album|relyear= 2013|certyear=2018|accessdate=December 7, 2018}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Yo Gotti}}\n\n[[Category:2013 albums]]\n[[Category:Yo Gotti albums]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Cool & Dre]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Honorable C.N.O.T.E.]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = I Am\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Yo Gotti]]\n| cover      = Yo Gotti I Am.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2013|11|19|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = 2012&ndash;13\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| length     = 49:28\n| label      = [[Collective Music Group|Collective]], [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*Benny Pough  {{small|([[executive producer|exec]].)}}\n*[[Sha Money XL]] {{small|(exec.)}}\n*[[Yo Gotti]] {{small|(exec.)}}\n*[[Arthur McArthur]]\n*[[Cool & Dre]]\n*David Versis\n*[[Honorable C.N.O.T.E.]]\n*Canei Finch\n*Greedy Money\n*[[DJ Infamous|Infamous]]\n*Jesse Wilson\n*[[Metro Boomin]]\n*Phatboiz\n*[[The HBK Gang|P-Lo]]\n*[[Lee On The Beats]]\n*[[Rich Homie Quan]]\n*Trauma Tone\n*The Youngstars\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Live from the Kitchen]]\n| prev_year  = 2012\n| next_title = [[The Art of Hustle]]\n| next_year  = 2016\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = I Am\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Act Right (Yo Gotti song)|Act Right]]\n | single1date = {{start date|2013|7|23|mf=yes}}\n | single2     = King Shit\n | single2date = {{start date|2013|10|7|mf=yes}}\n | single3     = Cold Blood\n | single3date = {{start date|2013|10|31|mf=yes}}\n | single4     = [[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\n | single4date = {{start date|2013|11|15|mf=yes}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''I Am''''' is the seventh [[studio album]] by American [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] recording artist [[Yo Gotti]]. The album was released on November 19, 2013, by [[Epic Records|Epic]] and CMG.<ref name=\"apple1\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/i-am/id722411780|title=iTunes - Music - I Am by Yo Gotti |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-11-19 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> The album features [[guest appearance]]s from [[T.I.]], [[Ne-Yo]], [[Wale (rapper)|Wale]], [[Rich Homie Quan]], [[J. Cole]], [[Young Jeezy|Jeezy]], [[Meek Mill]], and [[YG (rapper)|YG]], among others. The album was supported by the singles \"[[Act Right (Yo Gotti song)|Act Right]]\" featuring YG and Jeezy, \"King Shit\" featuring T.I., \"Cold Blood\" featuring J. Cole and Canei Finch and \"[[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\" featuring Rich Homie Quan. The first and fourth singles were later certified gold by the [[RIAA]].\n\n==Background==\nOn May 28, 2013, [[Yo Gotti]] announced that his sixth studio album would be titled ''I Am''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Homie |first=Big |url=http://rapradar.com/2013/07/31/new-video-yo-gotti-fuck-you/ |title=New Video: Yo Gotti \"Fuck You\" |publisher=Rap Radar |date=2013-07-31 |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref> In July 2013, it was announced that the album would be released on November 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Homie |first=Big |url=http://rapradar.com/2013/07/31/new-video-yo-gotti-fuck-you/ |title=New Video: Yo Gotti \"Fuck You\" |publisher=Rap Radar |date=2013-07-31 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> On August 22, 2013, he announced the ''I Am'' Tour Dates, a tour in promotion of ''I Am'' which ran from September 14, 2013, until November 19, 2013, with supporting acts including [[YG (rapper)|YG]], Zed Zilla, Shy Glizzy and [[Cash Out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/08/yo-gotti-announces-i-am-release-date-and-tour-dates-with-yg/ |title=Yo Gotti Announces 'I Am' Release Date And Tour Dates With YG - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=2013-08-22 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> On September 2, 2013, Yo Gotti released the mixtape ''Nov 19th: The Mixtape'' in promotion for the album.<ref>{{cite web|last=Mayorga |first=Dean |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25324/title.yo-gotti-nov-19th-the-mixtape-cover-art-tracklisting-download-mixtape-stream |title=Yo Gotti \"Nov 19th: The Mixtape\" Cover Art, Tracklisting, Download & Mixtape Stream |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2013-09-04 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref>\n\nIn a December 2013, interview with Mikey T The Movie Star, Yo Gotti spoke about how the album was received, saying: \"We gettin' nothin' but good, positive feedback from the album. The numbers going fairly well. Most important to me, the fans loved it. Fans fuck wit' it. ...Just givin' the people what they want. I've seen a lot of growth with this album. We doing different platforms, TV shows, we doing shows in different markets. Just being on different blog sites. I'm seeing a lot of different things coming. I guess it's because of the growth of the material that I put out on this album.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper |first=Roman |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26689/title.yo-gotti-says-he-s-grown-with-i-am-release |title=Yo Gotti Says He's Grown With \"I Am\" Release |publisher=HipHop DX |date= |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\nOn July 23, 2013, the album's first single \"[[Act Right (Yo Gotti song)|Act Right]]\" featuring [[Young Jeezy|Jeezy]] and [[YG (rapper)|YG]] was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/act-right-feat.-jeezy-yg-single/id672806616 |title=iTunes - Music - Act Right (feat. Jeezy & YG) - Single by Yo Gotti |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-07-23 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> On July 24, 2013, the music video for \"Act Right\" featuring Jeezy and YG was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2013/07/24/video-yo-gotti-f-young-jeezy-yg-act-right/ |title=Video: Yo Gotti f/ Young Jeezy & YG \u2013 'Act Right' |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2013-07-24 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> \"Act Right\" has since peaked at number 100 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/431628/yo-gotti/chart |title=Yo Gotti - Chart history |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=2013-10-22}}</ref> On October 7, 2013, the album's second official single \"King Shit\" featuring [[T.I.]] was released to [[mainstream urban]] radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1090&SingleID=3747 |title=Frequency News |publisher=Frequency News |date=2013-09-11 |access-date=2013-10-03 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005010142/http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1090&SingleID=3747 |archive-date=2013-10-05 |df= }}</ref> On October 15, 2013, the music video for \"King Shit\" featuring T.I. was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2013/10/15/video-yo-gotti-f-ti-king-shit/ |title=Video: Yo Gotti f/ T.I. \u2013 'King Sh*t' |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2013-10-15 |accessdate=2013-10-22}}</ref> \"King Shit\" has since peaked at five on the US ''Billboard'' [[Bubbling Under R&B/Hip-Hop Singles]] chart.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/277486/ti/chart?f=345 |title=T.I. - Chart history |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref>\n\nOn October 27, 2013, Yo Gotti premiered the album's third single, \"Cold Blood\" featuring rapper [[J. Cole]] and Canei Finch.<ref>{{cite web|author=Yo Gotti <!--end div name--> Follow @YoGottiKOM &nbsp; |url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/tracks/review/yo-gotti-cold-blood |title=Yo Gotti ft. J. Cole - Cold Blood &#124; Listen |publisher=Djbooth.net |date= |accessdate=2013-11-13}}</ref> Four days later on October 31, \"Cold Blood\" was serviced to mainstream urban radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1113&SingleID=3781 |title=Frequency News |publisher=Frequency News |date=2013-10-31 |accessdate=2013-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109123649/http://www.frequencynews.com/musiclibrary_detail.cfm?LabelID=141&ArtistID=60&AlbumID=1113&SingleID=3781 |archive-date=2013-11-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Then on November 19, 2013, \"Cold Blood\" was serviced to [[rhythmic contemporary]] radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.fmqb.com/article.asp?id=16691 |title=Radio Industry News, Music Industry Updates, Arbitron Ratings, Music News and more! |magazine=FMQB |access-date=2013-11-13 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403141710/http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=16691 |archive-date=2014-04-03 }}</ref> On February 5, 2014, the music video was released for \"Cold Blood\" featuring J. Cole and Canei Finch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/02/05/video-yo-gotti-f-j-cole-cold-blood/ |title=Video: Yo Gotti f/ J. Cole \u2013 'Cold Blood' |publisher=Rap-Up.com |date=2014-02-05 |accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\nOn November 20, 2013, the music video was released for \"LeBron James\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/11/yo-gotti-lebron-james-video |title=Yo Gotti \"LeBron James\" Video |magazine=Complex |date=2013-11-20 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref> On December 10, 2013, the music video was released for \"Don't Come Around\" featuring Kendall Morgan.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/12/yo-gotti-f-kendall-morgan-dont-come-around |title=Yo Gotti f/ Kendall Morgan \"Don't Come Around\" |magazine=Complex |accessdate=2013-12-11}}</ref> On November 15, 2013, \"[[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\" featuring [[Rich Homie Quan]] was released as the album's fourth single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/I-Know-Explicit/dp/B00GJ4LRJ4 |title=I Know feat. Rich Homie Quan [Explicit&#93;: Yo Gotti feat. Rich Homie Quan: MP3 Downloads |date=2013-11-15 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref> In January 2014, it was serviced to urban contemporary radio in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.promoonly.com/listings/view.php?issueid=15533&backup-view=1 |title=View Listing &#124; Promo Only: Music & Music Video |publisher=Promo Only |date= |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref> On May 1, 2014, the music video was released for \"I Know\" featuring Rich Homie Quan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/videos/id.16217/title.yo-gotti-f-rich-homie-quan-i-know- |title=Yo Gotti f. Rich Homie Quan - \"I Know\" |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2014-05-01 |accessdate=2014-05-17}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n|MC=64/100<ref name=\"metacritic1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/i-am/yo-gotti |title=I Am Reviews |website=Metacritic |date=2014-01-08 |accessdate=2014-02-04}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|author=David Jeffries |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/i-am-mw0002585418 |title=I Am - Yo Gotti &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |accessdate=2013-11-19}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Daily Cougar]]''\n| rev2Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thedailycougar.com/2013/11/23/review-yo-gottis-album/ |title=Review: Yo Gotti's album, 'I Am' |newspaper=The Daily Cougar |date=2013-11-23 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[HipHopDX]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"hiphopdx1\">{{cite web |last=Grant |first=Ronald |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.2184/title.yo-gotti-i-am |title=Yo Gotti - I Am |publisher=HipHop DX |date= |accessdate=2013-11-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131121013047/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/album-reviews/id.2184/title.yo-gotti-i-am |archive-date=2013-11-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Memphis Flyer]]''\n| rev4Score = (positive)<ref name=\"memphisflyer1\">{{cite web|last=Goggans |first=Louis |url=http://www.memphisflyer.com/CallingtheBluff/archives/2013/11/24/reppin-for-memphis-my-review-of-yo-gottis-i-am |title=Reppin' For Memphis: My Review of Yo Gotti's I Am |publisher=Memphis Flyer |date=2013-11-24 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>\n| rev5 = RapReviews\n| rev5Score = 4.5/10<ref name=\"rapreviews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2013_12_yogotti-iam.html |title=Yo Gotti :: I Am :: CMG/Epic Records |publisher=Rapreviews.com |date=2013-12-17 |accessdate=2014-01-03}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]''\n| rev6Score = (positive)<ref name=\"vibe\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/review-yo-gottis-i-am-excels-using-familiar-script |title=Review: Yo Gotti's 'I Am' Excels Using A Familiar Script |publisher=Vibe |date=2013-11-21 |accessdate=2013-11-29}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|2|4}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Jerry Shriver, Elysa Gardner, Brian Mansfield, USA TODAY |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2013/11/18/jake-bugg-yo-gotti-5-finger-death-punch-listen-up/3630325/ |title=Listen Up: Jake Bugg, Yo Gotti, 5 Finger Death Punch |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=2013-11-19 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''\n| rev8Score = 3/5 (L)<ref name=\"xxlmag1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/rap-music/reviews/2013/11/yo-gotti-i-am-album-review/ |title=Yo Gotti Mostly Stays True To His Soulful Memphis Sound On 'I Am' |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date=2013-11-21 |accessdate=2013-11-27}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''I Am'' was met with generally positive reviews from [[music criticism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 64, based on 5 reviews.<ref name=\"metacritic1\"/> David Jeffries of [[AllMusic]] gave the album four out of five stars, saying \"Like so many rappers who play it street level and live and die by the mixtape game, Memphis man Yo Gotti has maintained an uneasy relationship with the official album. His early work was indie to a fault, with long-players sounding patched together from mixtape numbers and other related whatnot, while his mainstream debut, 2012's ''Live from the Kitchen'', suffered from its long birthing process, sounding patched together on the million-dollar level with too much input from the marketing department. Good news for fans who stuck it out this long is that ''I Am'' is the moment when the skies clear, as the album comes on strong with a hard-hitting set of openers, and then, the high quality is maintained with a set of easy-flowing supportive songs that broaden the LP spectrum, all without leaving Gotti's comfort zone.\"<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> Ronald Grant of [[HipHopDX]] gave the album two and a half stars out of five, saying \"At the end of the day, ''I Am''\u2019s overall passable production and flashes of potency and strength keep it afloat for a time. And Gotti deserves commendation for his talent at bringing an explicit rawness, reality and affection to his autobiographical bars. But even those considerations aren\u2019t enough to make this album worth more than a few listens, sadly relying on a continuous set of monotonous hooks and overly used trap beats that saturate a strong majority of current popular Rap music.\"<ref name=\"hiphopdx1\"/> Reed Jackson of ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' gave the album an L, saying \"On the majority of ''I Am'', he stays rooted in the ideas and melodies that he\u2019s been refining since he first dropped ''From Da Dope Game 2 Da Rap Game'' over 10 year ago. The self-proclaimed \u201cKing Of Memphis\u201d has lived up to his title again, and perhaps this album will help him continue his reign for another 10 years.\"<ref name=\"xxlmag1\"/>\n\nPaul Cantor of ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' gave the album a positive review, saying \"If there\u2019s one glaring downside to ''I Am'', it\u2019s that a handful of songs sound, well, a lot like other songs. From the flows to the production, \u201cAct Right\u201d mimicks Young Jeezy\u2019s \u201cR.I.P.,\u201d and \u201cLebron James\u201d apes Juicy J\u2019s \u201cBandz A Make Her Dance.\u201d There are others. One on the one hand you applaud Gotti for implementing a hit-making formula so effectively, and after all, songs sounding like other songs is not an uncommon thing. But on the other hand, why couldn't Gotti couldn\u2019t come up with his own blueprint for smash records? Maybe after all these years he didn\u2019t want to leave too much up to chance. Not sure we can be mad at that.\"<ref name=\"vibe\"/> Grant Jones of RapReviews gave the album a 4.5 out of 10, saying \"This album slams harder than a body slam from Sticky Fingaz, and much like Onyx, ruthless misogyny runs throughout \"''I Am''\", with \u2018bitch' and \u2018nigga' in every other bar. At times you'd wish Gotti had done what DMX used to do and recorded two versions (of each song!), or even better, put some thought in to his writing. If you can get past the ignorance, this is enjoyable for what it is - an album to be played loudly in your car, with the windows down and a middle finger up to anybody who looks at you disapprovingly.\"<ref name=\"rapreviews1\"/> Louis Goggans of the ''[[Memphis Flyer]]'' gave the album a positive review, saying \"Gotti\u2019s transition from dominating the underground rap circuit to enjoying mainstream success with hits like \u201c5 Star\u201d and \u201cMen Lie, Women Lie\u201d convey that hard work pays off. And he continues to utilize the very same work ethic that's brought him to this point in his career on his latest project. Although Gotti doesn't sway too far from his usual topics on the album, he doesn't display any signs of decline creatively either. After more than 10 years in the game, Gotti still has the ability to provide listeners with quality music and this is evident with ''I Am''.\"<ref name=\"memphisflyer1\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nThe album debuted at number seven on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 48,000 copies in the United States, becoming Gotti's highest charting and best-selling album to date at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26422/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-11-24-2013|last=Tardio|first=Andres|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 11/24/2013|magazine=HipHopDX|date=2013-11-27|accessdate=2013-11-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131130024046/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26422/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-11-24-2013|archive-date=2013-11-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> In its second week the album sold 19,000 more copies.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26489/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-1-2013|last=Tardio|first=Andres|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 12/1/2013|magazine=HipHopDX|date=2013-12-04|accessdate=2013-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213000209/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26489/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-1-2013|archive-date=2013-12-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> In its third week the album sold 11,000 more copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tardio |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26580/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-8-2013 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: Week Ending 12/8/2013 |publisher=HipHop DX |date= |accessdate=2013-12-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213060438/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26580/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-8-2013/ |archive-date=2013-12-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In its fourth week the album sold 10,000 more copies.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26666/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-15-2013|last=Tardio|first=Andres|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 12/15/2013|magazine=HipHopDX|date=2013-12-18|accessdate=2013-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219031704/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26666/title.hip-hop-album-sales-week-ending-12-15-2013|archive-date=2013-12-19|url-status=dead}}</ref> As of August 2015, the album has sold 212,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150825183753/http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |archivedate= August 25, 2015 |url=http://hitsdailydouble.com/new_album_releases |title=Upcoming Releases |website=Hits Daily Double |publisher=HITS Digital Ventures }}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Ceremony\n! Category\n! Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"| 2014\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[2014 BET Hip Hop Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Nostro|first1=Lauren|title=Here Are the 2014 BET Hip-Hop Award Nominees|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2014/09/2014-bet-hip-hop-award-nominees|work=Complex|publisher=Complex Media|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n|Album of the Year\n|rowspan=\"1\" {{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1 = I Am\n| note1 = \n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Yo Gotti|Mario Mims]]|Philipp Hurtt|Walter Sigler|Kazumi Tabarak}} \n| extra1 = [[Cool & Dre]]\n| length1 = 3:04\n\n| title2 = Don't Come Around\n| note2 = featuring Kendall Morgan\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Mims|Kendall Morgan|Alexander Izquierdo}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|[[DJ Infamous|Infamous]]|Alexander Izquierdo}}\n| length2 = 3:10\n\n| title3 = [[I Know (Yo Gotti song)|I Know]]\n| note3 = featuring [[Rich Homie Quan]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Mim|Denzel Foster|Jay King|[[Rich Homie Quan|Dequantes Lamar]]|Thomas McElroy}} \n| extra3 = {{hlist|Trauma Tone|[[Rich Homie Quan]]}}\n| length3 = 4:19\n\n| title4 = Sorry\n| note4 = \n| writer4 = Mims\n| extra4 = Greedy Money\n| length4 = 3:16\n\n| title5 = F-U\n| note5 = featuring [[Meek Mill]]\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Mims|[[Meek Mill|Robert Williams]]|Millie Jackson|Randy Klein}}\n| extra5 = Infamous\n| length5 = 3:05\n\n| title6 = Pride To the Side\n| note6 = \n| wr